## The Architect of Creation

In the genesis of Mundus, **Lorkhan** had the idea — but it was **Magnus** who translated it into architectural reality. Magnus was the most brilliant of the et-Ada, the master craftsman whose genius made it possible to design the plans of a functioning world. Without him, Lorkhan's vision would have remained an impossible dream; through him, it became a perfectly engineered prison.

### The Role of Magnus

Magnus was neither a mere executor nor a blind accomplice. His role in the Creation was that of a **divine architect**:

- He conceived the fundamental structure of Mundus — the physical laws, the flow of time, the primordial geography
- He coordinated the other Aedra, assigning each a role in the Construction
- He drafted the plans the spirits followed to give form to the world
- He established the conduits of magical energy linking Mundus to Aetherius

### The Question of Complicity

Did Magnus know that the Creation would cost the participants their divine essence? The texts diverge. Some present him as yet another victim of Lorkhan's deception. Others suggest he understood the trap — but too late, once the plans had already been drawn and the Construction had begun.

## The Great Escape

### The Abandonment

When the truth became clear — when the Aedra realized they were draining their own substance to fuel the Creation — Magnus made a decision that some call cowardly and others call wisdom: he **fled**.

Unlike the other Aedra who remained trapped in their own work, Magnus had the power and presence of mind to withdraw before the trap snapped shut completely. He wrenched his essence from Mundus and crossed the layers of reality to return to **Aetherius** — the realm of pure magicka from which the spirits had originally come.

### The Creation of the Sun

Magnus's flight was not a quiet affair. In crossing the membranes separating Mundus from Aetherius, he **tore reality itself**, leaving a gaping wound in the fabric of the sky — a permanent hole through which the light and energy of Aetherius pour endlessly onto Mundus.

That hole is the **Sun**.

The sunlight on Nirn is not that of a burning star as mortals might imagine. It is the **pure light of Aetherius** seeping through the breach Magnus left behind. That is why sunlight is intrinsically linked to magic — it is literally raw magicka made visible.

## The Magna-Ge: Those Who Followed

### The Stars

Magnus did not flee alone. Countless lesser spirits — his assistants, his apprentices, his followers — imitated him and in turn pierced the veil of Mundus. Each of their flights left a smaller tear. These tears are the **stars**.

The spirits who followed Magnus are collectively called the **Magna-Ge** (the "children of Magnus"). Like their master, they abandoned the Creation to return to Aetherius, leaving behind those thousands of points of light that pierce the night sky.

### The Constellations

The scholars of Tamriel have organized the stars into **constellations** — and each constellation exerts an observable influence on the mortal world. Birth signs, astral prophecies, and certain forms of divination rest on the study of these "wounds in the sky." The thirteen principal constellations are linked to the most powerful Magna-Ge among Magnus's followers.

## Magnus and Magic

### The Source of All Magicka

Magic on Nirn comes directly from the sun and the stars — that is, from the openings toward Aetherius created by Magnus and the Magna-Ge. **Magicka** is the raw energy of Aetherius, filtered through these breaches and absorbed by beings gifted with mystical sensitivity.

This relationship explains several phenomena:

1. Magic is more powerful during the day (when Magnus's "hole" is visible)
2. Certain spells are affected by the stars and constellations
3. The undead fear sunlight — it is the pure magicka that harms them
4. The **Eye of Magnus** (an artifact discovered at Saarthal) concentrates this energy in a terrifying way

### The Eye of Magnus

The **Eye of Magnus** is an artifact of immeasurable power, discovered beneath the ruins of **Saarthal** in Skyrim. Its exact nature is debated:

- Some believe it is a fragment of Magnus's power, abandoned during his flight
- Others theorize it is a tool Magnus used to construct Mundus
- The **Staff of Magnus** is said to be the key to controlling it

The Eye was at the center of the crisis at the **College of Winterhold** in 4E 201, when the Thalmor agent **Ancano** attempted to exploit its power, threatening to destroy all of Tamriel.

## The Cult of Magnus

### Across Different Cultures

Magnus is not venerated the same way everywhere:

- **The Altmer** regard him as one of the wisest of spirits — the one with the intelligence to flee
- **The Psijic Order** holds a particular respect for Magnus as the source of their art
- **The Nords** have no strong tradition around Magnus, though some scholars associate him with minor legends
- **The Empire** acknowledges him as the source of magic but does not include him among the Eight (then Nine) Divines

### Aedra or Not?

The classification of Magnus is problematic. Technically, he participated in the Creation of Mundus — which would qualify him as an Aedra. However, he withdrew before completion and did not sacrifice his essence like the others. He is not trapped in a celestial body like the Divines. He exists in Aetherius, free and powerful, in a state some compare more closely to that of a Daedric Prince.

## The Legacy of the Flight

### What It Means

Magnus's flight is a founding event whose consequences still shape the world:

- Without it, there would be **no magic** — the membranes would remain intact and magicka would not flow toward Mundus
- Without it, there would be **no natural light** — Mundus would be plunged into eternal darkness
- His flight proved that **escape was possible** — perhaps inspiring the Altmer in their quest to transcend mortality

Magnus is thus the paradox of a creator who abandoned his creation — and whose abandonment may have been the greatest gift he could give to the world he had built.
